## On generational collection itself:

If you *have* verified all the above and listeners are genuinely accumulating despite proper removal attempts, then yes - tracking listener lifecycles could help *diagnosis*. But I wouldn't implement mark-and-sweep for *cleanup* because:

- EventEmitter already tracks listeners in arrays
- You can't reliably detect "orphaned" listeners without understanding the application logic
- Aggressive collection could break legitimate pending operations

**What you CAN do effectively:**
```javascript
// Track listener lifecycle without GC implications
class ListenerAnalytics {
  constructor(emitter) {
    this.emitter = emitter;
    this.createdAt = new Map();
    this.firedAt = new Map();
  }

  trackListener(eventName, listener) {
    const id = Symbol();
    this.createdAt.set(id, Date.now());

    const wrapper = (...args) => {
      this.firedAt.set(id, Date.now());
      return listener(...args);
    };

    return { id, wrapper };
  }

  getStaleListeners(maxAgeMs = 60000) {
    // Report listeners created but never fired
    const now = Date.now();
    const stale = [];

    this.createdAt.forEach((createdTime, id) => {
      if (!this.firedAt.has(id) && (now - createdTime) > maxAgeMs) {
        stale.push(id);
      }
    });

    return stale; // diagnostics, not cleanup
  }
}
```

This tells you *what's wrong* without trying to auto-fix it.

